article.description:
Tamika Whitmore scored 26 points and Tan
White had 10 of her 18 in the fourth quarter as the Indiana Fever
staged their biggest comeback of the season to defeat the San
Antonio Silver Stars 76-70 Saturday night.
article.headline: Fever heat up to overcome 16-point deficit, Silver Stars
article.linkText: Fever heat up to overcome 16-point deficit, Silver Stars
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS -- The Indiana Fever got a jolt from the crowd
and responded with the fourth-biggest comeback victory in franchise
history.

	   Tamika Whitmore scored 26 points and Tan White had 10 of her 18
in the fourth quarter as the Fever capitalized on a
franchise-record 21 steals to defeat the San Antonio Silver Stars
76-70 Saturday night.

	   Indiana trailed by 16 twice in the third quarter -- the last time
at 55-39 midway in the period. The Stars still had a double-digit
lead at 66-55 with seven minutes to play. White then hit a
3-pointer to ignite an 11-point Indiana run over a span of three
minutes.

	   Tully Bevilaqua, who had five of her career-high seven steals in
the fourth quarter, said the crowd of 8,003 was one of the loudest
of the season at Conseco Fieldhouse.

	   "We were probably a little passive in the first half, but we
picked up the intensity and the crowd came for the ride with us. We
heard them and it was just awesome to the end,'' she said.

	   The Fever (19-11) tied the game on a hook shot by White and took
the lead for good when she hit two free throws that put Indiana
ahead 67-66 with 3:35 remaining.

	   Tamika Catchings, who had 18 for Indiana, gave the Fever their
biggest lead of the night, 73-67, by converting a three-point play
with 2:15 left.

	   San Antonio cut its deficit in half on a 3-pointer by Agnieszke
Bibrzycka with 46 seconds to go. It was the first field goal by the
Stars in nearly seven minutes. San Antonio missed five consecutive
shots and had seven of its 28 turnovers in that span.

	   "For the first time I really just saw in our faces, and in our
team, that undying will to win and we just refused to lose,'' said
Whitmore, who had eight points in the final quarter when the Fever
went on a 21-4 run in the final seven minutes.

	   Bibrzycka, Shannon Johnson and Shanna Zolman scored 14 each as
the Stars (12-18) lost their fourth straight game. Johnson had 12
of her points in the third period before straining her left ankle
with 4:29 remaining in the period. She had the ankle treated, but
was only able to return for 57 seconds in the fourth quarter before
limping back to the bench.

	   "We made stops when we needed to,'' Indiana coach Brian Winters
said. "The main thing is we got stops and steals.''

	   The comeback was the biggest this season, topping the mark of 14
when Indiana trailed the New York Liberty on June 13 before
recording an 80-70 victory in overtime. The last time Indiana won a
game after trailing by more than 16 points was July 1, 2001, when
it trailed Phoenix by 19 on July 1, 2001, and came back to post an
86-78 overtime victory.

	   "They were the aggressor and we couldn't handle their
pressure,'' Zolman said. "We played well defensively, but then we
were unable to convert baskets from our defense.''

	   Indiana also had a season-high seven steals by Catchings, who
came into the game leading the league with an average of 2.85 per
game.

	   San Antonio opened a 39-34 halftime edge as it shot 59 percent
from the field (16-of-37), overcoming 12 turnovers in the process.
Indiana had fewer turnovers (seven), but shot only 39 percent
(14-of-36) in the first half.

	   Zolman and Shyra Ely, both former high school stars in Indiana
who went on to star for Tennessee, came off the bench to spark the
Stars from long range. Zolman contributed three 3-pointers and Ely
two to help San Antonio open a 33-22 lead. Indiana got back into
the game with an 8-2 run.
